Using of Android Studio
1) Install Android Studio: https://developer.android.com/studio
2) After downloading, run the installer.
3) A dialog box should pop up. Do not Import Settings, Just Click "Ok"
4) Click “Next" to go thru the Wizard
5) Click “Next” to do a Standard install
6) Choose light or dark theme for your editor and click “Next”
7) Click “Finish”
8) You will likely get a dialog box pop and say “HAXM Installation wants to make changes”. 
   Enter your password and click OK
9) If you get a “System Extension Blocked” error, follow the prompt to Open 
   Security Preferences and click “Allow” for “Intel Corporation Apps”
10) Once the HAXM installer finished you should get a dialog box from Android Studio.

# Android Simulator
1) At bottom of the screen click on "Configure", select “AVD Manager”
2) Creating a new Virtual Device
	2.1) Click “Create New Virtual Device”
	2.2) Select a Device from the list and click “Next”
	2.3) If the System Image for the most recent SDK is not installed, you will need to click the "Download" link next to the SDK version.
	2.4) After the image has been downloaded, click “Next”
	2.5) Preview the settings and then click “Finish”
	2.6) You should see the newly created device in the “Your Virtual Device” screen.
3) Running the simulator
	3.1) Click the Play ▶️button all the way to the right in the "Actions" column.
	3.2) This will open an Android simulator on your machine. If everything is working well, 
	     it should load a generic screen with a few apps.
	3.3) Go to your terminal and in your React Native project directory, run npm start
	3.4) web interface "RN Bundler" opens up in your browser, click on the option 
	     to “Run on Android simulator”
	3.5) If you navigate back to your Android simulator you might see 
	     a “Permit Drawing Over Other Apps” message. Click the OK button and 
		 it should take you to the system settings screen to enable this. 
		 You will likely have to go back to the Metro Bundler and select “Run on Android simulator” again.
	3.6) This will launch the Expo application in the simulated device and run your bundled code. 
	     Eventually, it should load the “Hi There!” screen.